CPIAUCSL~CPIAUCSL~2001-01-06~2001-01-06~Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers: All Items~1947-01-01~2000-11-01~Monthly~M~Index 1982-1984=100~Index 1982-1984=100~Seasonally Adjusted~SA~2008-12-16 14:45:08-06~94.0~95.0~"The Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers: All Items (CPIAUCSL) is a price index of a basket of goods and services paid by urban consumers. Percent changes in the price index measure the inflation rate between any two time periods. The most common inflation metric is the percent change from one year ago. It can also represent the buying habits of urban consumers. This particular index includes roughly 88 percent of the total population
column2: accounting for wage earners
column4: technical workers
column9: and those not in the labor force.

column1: The CPIs are based on prices for food
column2: clothing
column4: and fuels; transportation fares; service fees (e.g.
column5: water and sewer service); and sales taxes. Prices are collected monthly from about 4
column7: 000 retail establishments across 87 urban areas. To calculate the index
column8: price changes are averaged with weights representing their importance in the spending of the particular group. The index measures price changes (as a percent change) from a predetermined reference date. In addition to the original unadjusted index distributed
column9: the Bureau of Labor Statistics also releases a seasonally adjusted index. The unadjusted series reflects all factors that may influence a change in prices. However
column10: it can be very useful to look at the seasonally adjusted CPI
column11: which removes the effects of seasonal changes

column1: The CPI can be used to recognize periods of inflation and deflation. Significant increases in the CPI within a short time frame might indicate a period of inflation
column2: and significant decreases in CPI within a short time frame might indicate a period of deflation. However
column3: because the CPI includes volatile food and oil prices
column4: it might not be a reliable measure of inflationary and deflationary periods. For a more accurate detection
column5: the core CPI (CPILFESL (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPILFESL)) is often used. When using the CPI
column6: please note that it is not applicable to all consumers and should not be used to determine relative living costs. Additionally
column7: the CPI is a statistical measure vulnerable to sampling error since it is based on a sample of prices and not the complete average.

column1: For more information on the consumer price indexes
column2: see:

TCU~TCU~2001-01-06~2001-01-06~Capacity Utilization: Total Industry~1967-01-01~2000-11-01~Monthly~M~Percent of Capacity~% of Capacity~Seasonally Adjusted~SA~2005-09-30 01:08:59-05~69.0~69.0~"Capacity Utilization: Total Industry (TCU) is the percentage of resources used by corporations and factories to produce goods in manufacturing
column2: mining
column3: and electric and gas utilities for all facilities located in the United States (excluding those in U.S. territories).(1) We can also think of capacity utilization as how much capacity is being used from the total available capacity to produce demanded finished products.

column1: Capacity utilization indexes are constructed for 71 industries in manufacturing
column2: 16 in mining
column3: and 2 in utilities. (1) Physical data on capacity utilization are primarily compiled from trade sources and government sources
column4: such as the U.S. Geological Survey and the U.S. Energy Information Administration.(1) When physical data are unavailable
column5: capacity utilization data are compiled from the U.S. Census Bureau’s Quarterly Survey of Plant Capacity Utilization
column6: which provides data for almost 70 percent of total industry capacity.(1) Additionally
column7: the capacity index is developed on a monthly basis
column8: designed to be consistent with the production index.(1)

column1: According to the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System
column2: the capacity index tries to conceptualize the idea of sustainable maximum output
column3: which is defined as the highest level of output a plant can sustain within the confines of its resources. The Board of Governors defines the seasonally adjusted capacity utilization rate as the output index divided by the capacity index. The capacity utilization rate can also implicitly describe how efficiently the factors of production (inputs in the production process) are being used. (1) It sheds light on how much more firms can produce without additional costs. Additionally
column4: this rate gives manufacturers some idea as to how much consumer demand they will be able to meet in the future.

column1: The Federal Reserve strives to construct a capacity index consistent with time by using different relevant data sources.(1) Developing an index that is reasonable given the time period is the primary aim for this index
column2: but there are still some difficulties. Extensive technological and structural changes have and will continue to occur
column3: affecting the degree of tightness the Federal Reserve index of capacity utilization will represent.(2) In addition
column4: each series of capacity utilization is flawed by commission; therefore
column5: they should be used with caution.(2)

column1: References
(1) Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System. “Industrial Production and Capacity Utilization.” Statistical release G.17;. May 15
(2) Bauer
column2: Paul W. and Deily
column3: Mary E. “A User’s Guide to Capacity- Utilization Measures.” Economic Commentary. Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland
column4: July 1

column1: FEDFUNDS~FEDFUNDS~2001-01-06~2001-01-06~Effective Federal Funds Rate~1954-07-01~2000-12-01~Monthly~M~Percent~%~Not Seasonally Adjusted~NSA~2006-06-07 15:46:44-05~98.0~99.0~"Averages of daily figures.

The federal funds rate is the interest rate at which depository institutions trade federal funds (balances held at Federal Reserve Banks) with each other overnight. When a depository institution has surplus balances in its reserve account
column2: it lends to other banks in need of larger balances. In simpler terms
column4: which is often referred to as liquidity
column5: will lend to another bank that needs to quickly raise liquidity. (1) The rate that the borrowing institution pays to the lending institution is determined between the two banks; the weighted average rate for all of these types of negotiations is called the effective federal funds rate.(2) The effective federal funds rate is essentially determined by the market but is influenced by the Federal Reserve through open market operations to reach the federal funds rate target.(2)

column1: The Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meets eight times a year to determine the federal funds target rate. As previously stated
column2: this rate influences the effective federal funds rate through open market operations or by buying and selling of government bonds (government debt).(2) More specifically
column3: the Federal Reserve decreases liquidity by selling government bonds
column4: thereby raising the federal funds rate because banks have less liquidity to trade with other banks. Similarly
column5: the Federal Reserve can increase liquidity by buying government bonds
column6: decreasing the federal funds rate because banks have excess liquidity for trade. Whether the Federal Reserve wants to buy or sell bonds depends on the state of the economy. If the FOMC believes the economy is growing too fast and inflation pressures are inconsistent with the dual mandate of the Federal Reserve
column7: the Committee may set a higher federal funds rate target to temper economic activity. In the opposing scenario
column8: the FOMC may set a lower federal funds rate target to spur greater economic activity. Therefore
column9: the FOMC must observe the current state of the economy to determine the best course of monetary policy that will maximize economic growth while adhering to the dual mandate set forth by Congress. In making its monetary policy decisions
column10: the FOMC considers a wealth of economic data
column11: such as: trends in prices and wages

column1: The federal funds rate is the central interest rate in the U.S. financial market. It influences other interest rates such as the prime rate
column2: which is the rate banks charge their customers with higher credit ratings. Additionally
column3: the federal funds rate indirectly influences longer- term interest rates such as mortgages
column4: loans
column6: all of which are very important to consumer wealth and confidence.(2)

column1: References
(1) Federal Reserve Bank of New York. “Federal funds.” Fedpoints
column2: August 2007.

column1: (2) Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System. “Monetary Policy”. http://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/default.htm."~131

PAYEMS~PAYEMS~2001-01-06~2001-01-06~All Employees: Total Nonfarm Payrolls~1939-01-01~2000-12-01~Monthly~M~Thousands of Persons~Thous. of Persons~Seasonally Adjusted~SA~2009-02-06 10:52:55-06~83.0~83.0~"All Employees: Total Nonfarm
column2: commonly known as Total Nonfarm Payroll
column3: is a measure of the number of U.S. workers in the economy that excludes proprietors
column4: private household employees
column7: and the unincorporated self-employed. This measure accounts for approximately 80 percent of the workers who contribute to Gross Domestic Product (GDP).

column1: This measure provides useful insights into the current economic situation because it can represent the number of jobs added or lost in an economy. Increases in employment might indicate that businesses are hiring which might also suggest that businesses are growing. Additionally
column2: those who are newly employed have increased their personal incomes
column3: which means (all else constant) their disposable incomes have also increased
column4: thus fostering further economic expansion.

column1: Generally
column2: the U.S. labor force and levels of employment and unemployment are subject to fluctuations due to seasonal changes in weather
column4: and the opening and closing of schools. The Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) adjusts the data to offset the seasonal effects to show non-seasonal changes: for example
column5: women's participation in the labor force; or a general decline in the number of employees
column6: a possible indication of a downturn in the economy. To closely examine seasonal and non-seasonal changes
column7: the BLS releases two monthly statistical measures: the seasonally adjusted All Employees: Total Nonfarm (PAYEMS) and All Employees: Total Nonfarm (PAYNSA)

column1: The series comes from the 'Current Employment Statistics (Establishment Survey).'
The source code is: CES0000000001"~50

The Unemployment Level is the aggregate measure of people currently unemployed in the US. Someone in the labor force is defined as unemployed if they were not employed during the survey reference week
column2: were available for work
column3: and made at least one active effort to find a job during the 4-week survey period.

column1: The Unemployment Level is collected in the CPS and published by the BLS. It is provided on a monthly basis
column2: so this data is used in part by macroeconomists as an initial economic indicator of current trends. The Unemployment Level helps government agencies
column4: and researchers gauge the overall health of the economy.

column1: Note that individuals that are not employed but not actively looking for a job are not counted as unemployed. For instance
column2: declines in the Unemployment Level may either reflect movements of unemployed individuals into the labor force because they found a job
column3: or movements of unemployed individuals out of the labor force because they stopped looking to find a job.

column1: For more information
column2: see:

column1: U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics
column2: CES Overview (https://www.bls.gov/web/empsit/cesprog.htm)

column1: U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics
column2: BLS Handbook of Methods: Chapter 2. Employment
column4: and Earnings from the Establishment Survey (https://www.bls.gov/opub/hom/pdf/ces-20110307.pdf)"~50
